----------- Linear Regression
y=b0+b1x
residuals: predicted value - observed value

minimizing the error function:
J(b0,b1) =  min < 1/2m * SUM_(from i=1 to m) ( (b0 + b1 * x1_{observed}) - Y_{observed} ) ^ 2> 
----   The 1ùëö is to "average" the squared error over the number of components so that the number of components doesn't affect the function (see John's answer). 
-----  So now the question is why there is an extra 1/2. In short, it doesn't matter. The solution that minimizes ùêΩ as you have written it will also minimize 2ùêΩ=1ùëö‚àëùëñ(‚Ñé(ùë•ùëñ)‚àíùë¶ùëñ)2. The latter function, 2ùêΩ, may seem more "natural," but the factor of 2 does not matter when optimizing.
------ The only reason some authors like to include it is because when you take the derivative with respect to ùë•, the 2 goes away.

Sum of Squared Error (SSE):  sum_(from i to m) (y_{b} (x^1) - y^i_{obs}) ^ 2
Total Sum of Squre (TSS):  sum_(from i to m) ( [y_{obs}] bar - y^i_{obs}) ^ 2
Coefficient of Determination:(R^2) = 1 - SSE/TSS =  (TSS ‚àí RSS)/TSS
          --   the proportion of the variance for a dependent variable that's explained by an independent variable or variables in a regression model.


